cs.NI, cs.IT, cs.SY, cs.AR, cs.CE 

Reasoning: 
1. cs.NI (Networking and Internet Architecture) - The paper discusses the use of Wi-Fi for IoT communications and proposes an asymmetric design for the PHY layer of transceiver design. This falls under the scope of networking and internet architecture. 
2. cs.IT (Information Theory) - The paper discusses the use of OFDM for IoT communications and proposes a design that exploits asymmetric clock rates. This involves information theory concepts such as channel coding and modulation. 
3. cs.SY (Systems and Control) - The proposed design involves controlling the power and computational resources of the AP and IoT devices to optimize power and spectrum efficiency. This falls under the scope of systems and control. 
4. cs.AR (Hardware Architecture) - The paper proposes a new design for the PHY layer of transceiver design that involves exploiting the clock rates of the AP and IoT devices. This involves hardware architecture considerations. 
5. cs.CE (Computational Engineering, Finance, and Science) - The paper proposes a design that utilizes the computational resources of the AP to trade for the transmission power of IoT devices. This falls under the scope of computational engineering.
